T1  - Gender Differences in Stereotypes of Risk Preferences: Experimental Evidence from a Matrilineal and a Patrilineal Society
AU  - Pondorfer, Andreas
AU  - Barsbai, Toman
AU  - Schmidt, Ulrich
Y1  - 2016/08/11
PY  - 2016
DA  - 2017/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2016.2505
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2016.2505
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 3268
EP  - 3284
VL  - 63
IS  - 10
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - We use a controlled experiment to analyze gender differences in stereotypes about risk preferences of men and women across two distinct island societies in the Pacific: the patrilineal Palawan in the Philippines and the matrilineal Teop in Papua New Guinea. We find no gender differences in actual risk preferences, but we find evidence for culture-specific stereotypes. Like men in Western societies, Palawan men overestimate women?s actual risk aversion. By contrast, Teop men underestimate women?s actual risk aversion. We argue that the observed differences in stereotypes between the two societies are determined by the different social status of women. Data are available at http://dx.doi.org/10.1287/mnsc.2016.2505. This paper was accepted by Uri Gneezy, behavioral economics.
AB  - We use a controlled experiment to analyze gender differences in stereotypes about risk preferences of men and women across two distinct island societies in the Pacific: the patrilineal Palawan in the Philippines and the matrilineal Teop in Papua New Guinea. We find no gender differences in actual risk preferences, but we find evidence for culture-specific stereotypes. Like men in Western societies, Palawan men overestimate women?s actual risk aversion. By contrast, Teop men underestimate women?s actual risk aversion. We argue that the observed differences in stereotypes between the two societies are determined by the different social status of women. Data are available at http://dx.doi.org/10.1287/mnsc.2016.2505. This paper was accepted by Uri Gneezy, behavioral economics.
